{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:13:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:13:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17811"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17811"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0,0,0.97]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10525"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73222"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10525"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58693"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9893"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25000"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73222"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESurface tension forces in the alveoli of the lung play a crucial role in respiratory physiology.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of pulmonary surfactant?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevents fluid accumulation in the alveoli","Maintains alveolar pH balance","Protects against inhaled pathogens","Facilitates gas exchange across the alveolar membrane","Reduces alveolar surface tension to prevent collapse"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of pulmonary surfactant is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduces alveolar surface tension to prevent collapse\u003C/strong\u003E. Without surfactant, the surface tension of the fluid lining the alveoli would be so high that alveoli would collapse during expiration. This would lead to atelectasis and severely impaired gas exchange.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents fluid accumulation in the alveoli\u003C/strong\u003E - Fluid accumulation in the alveoli is primarily prevented through oncotic and hydrostatic pressure gradients rather than surfactant action.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains alveolar pH balance\u003C/strong\u003E - The alveolar pH balance is maintained through bicarbonate buffering and ventilation mechanisms rather than surfactant.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtects against inhaled pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E - Although surfactant proteins have minor immunological properties, this is not their main physiological role.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates gas exchange across the alveolar membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - While normal gas exchange requires surfactant presence, surfactant does not directly facilitate the diffusion process itself.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003ESurfactant is particularly important in small alveoli where surface tension forces would otherwise be greatest according to LaPlace\u0027s law. Premature infants who lack adequate surfactant can develop respiratory distress syndrome due to alveolar collapse.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary surfactant reduces alveolar surface tension to prevent alveolar collapse during expiration.","Surfactant is composed primarily of phospholipids, especially dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine.","Surface tension is highest in small alveoli without surfactant, making them prone to collapse according to LaPlace\u0027s law."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58693"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17811"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58693"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T09:20:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T09:20:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10525"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73222"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updated